Goal:
The purpose of the test is to have 2 threads of a single minion in an infinite loop, accessing a shared resource
with different timing alignments to try to find starvation problems.
For further details see: $REPOROOT/dv/tests/minion_core/c_asm_tests/starvation/rtlmin_6068/testCases.xlsx

Details:
The following is copied from an E-mail sent by Sebastia Tortella.
Take this example, for instance: both threads try to use the integer div/mul this way:

thread0:                   thread1:         
  nop (N0 times)              nop (M0 times)
  div                         div 
  nop (N1 times)              nop (M1 times)
  j thread0                   j thread1

And repeat that for different values of N0, N1, M0, M1.
For example, and instance with (N0, N1)= (1,0) and (M0,M1)=(1,1) would have the following timing:
T0: NOP, DIV, NOP, DIV, NOP, DIV, NOP, DIV, NOP, DIV, NOP, DIV, NOP, DIV, NOP...
T1: NOP, DIV, NOP, NOP, DIV, NOP, NOP, DIV, NOP, NOP, DIV, NOP, NOP, DIV, NOP...

The idea is to sweep for different ranges of these parameters (Ni and Mi) to test all possible alignments to try to
find situations where the div block is being monopolized by one thread and the other one cannot go forward. That would
happen (if there was no RTL mechanism preventing it) if one thread does a DIV followed by a number of nops such as to
request again a div at the same cycle the div becomes available (and the other thread cannot use the div because it
is never scheduled at that precise cycle). So I'd say the number of nops in this case that would be relevant would be
values close to the equivalent time the division takes.

 - You can do that with either an external tool such as a python script generating an assembly code with all these
   combinations, or what I did in the test with c++ templates.

Why templates and not regular function parameters? Take the following 2 C++ functions:

template<size_t count>                   |  
static void ALWAYS_INLINE nops1() {      |  void nops2(size_t count) {      
  __asm__ __volatile__                   |  for (size_t i = 0; i< count; i++)
    (                                    |      asm("nop");                  
     ".rept %0\n"                        |  }                                
     "nop\n"                             |                                  
     ".endr\n"                           |
     : : "i" (count) );                  |
}                                        |

The dissasembly they'd produce for nops1<5>() and nops2(N) would be:
             nop                           |    li t0, 4
           nop                           |    1:
           nop                           |    nop
           nop                           |    addi t0, t0, -1
           nop                           |    bne t0, zero, 1b

As you can see each different specialization of nops1<N> creates a function with exactly the number of nops we want,
instead of doing a loop and the function being reused for each value of N. I want the first one to create the test
pattern, not the second one.

That was the introduction. Let's get briefly into the test specifics:

The test expects all minions of a neighbourhood to be active and with both threads. For each neigh:
 - thread 0 is the control thread, thread 1 is unused
 - threads 2 to 15 are the test threads


For each iteration of the test,
   - test threads enter an infinite loop
   - the control thread waits for a certain amount of time (constant EXPECTED_CYCLES) and notifies the test threads
     with a msip int so that they exit the infinite loop.
In the minion_diags.py, there is the "+thread_timeout=3000" option, which is smaller than the default. If a thread
doesn't retire instruction in 3000 cycles, then the test fails (this 3000 is less than the expected_cycles)

In $MINION_DIAGS/starvation/common you'll find 2 classes:
 starvationTest.h => class starvation_test_base (to define the thread loops)
 starvation.h => class starvation (for test loop code and test cases definition)
To define a test, you'll need to make classes derived from them. All the sync code, loop control, code alignment...
is hidden inside these 2 base classes

- For the test loop code, make a class inheriting from starvation_test_base. You need to define this virtual functions:
         void setup() => to be executed before the test (e.g. setup offsets for gsc)
         first_thread_iter()  => what one of the threads will do in a loop
         second_thread_iter() => what the other thread will do in a loop  

The idea is that the class you define is templatized with things you want to be variable (e.g. number of nops in the
div example)
See rtlmin_6068.h for an example

- To define the test case, you'll need to inherit from 'starvation' and define the run_tests method. See any of the
rtlmin_6068_X.cc for examples.
I added the 'make_test' class to help define sweeps for the template parameters of the test code class.
 auto table = make_tests< gsc_starvation_test,  // test class name (which has N template parameters)
                        range<Mx,Mn,Inc>,       // first parameter of the test class range (from mx to mn with
                                                // increments of inc)
                        range<Mx2,Mn2,Inc2>,    // second parameter
                        ...
                  > ::sweep();                 // to generate all combinations of parametes with the ranges you defined
                  > ::random<COUNT,SEED>();    // to generate COUNT random combinations of parameters within the
                                               // ranges you defined

Some final notes:
- I added using x31 as an iteration counter to make the test self checking (if there are less than a threshold
  number of iterations in the infinite loops when the MSIP arrives, the test fails)
- inheritance and virtual functions is done via the so called CRPT in order to have static polymorphism (and void
  the virtual method overhead, which maybe does not even work with the way we load the elfs into the simulations)